            <h2>Filed under 'amazon'</h2>
                

    



<h3 class="date"><a href="/2010/dec/30/">&#x27a0;</a> December 30, 2010</h3>


<div class="row">
    <div class="span12">


    
    <div class="well" id="lending-kindle-books" >

        

        <h4><a class="taggedlink linklink" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/help/customer/display.html/ref=hp_left_sib?ie=UTF8&amp;nodeId=200549320">Lending Kindle Books</a></h4>

        
            
        

        <p>Just launched, Amazon now let you &#8220;lend&#8221; Kindle books. A fab feature, but sadly crippled in this (initial?) form.</p>

<p>1) You need to initiate the process from Amazon.com &#8212; you can&#8217;t do it from a Kindle<br />2) Publishers have the right to disable lending, and a quick scan through my Kindle purchases show that most large publishers have blanket blocks in place.<br />3) Loans are currently limited to 14 days, and you can lend a book once and only once. Publishers currently cannot adjust these limits.</p>

<p>Despite these gripes, this is clearly a big step in the right direction.  Hopefully this is just Amazon&#8217;s first stab at shifting the digital-media-lending Overton window.</p>

        <div class="row-fluid">
